To add to this and to explain why this era's 'economic commanding heights ' manufacturing is different - it's software enabled. For example an EV,  smartphone, drone and obviously a robot, rely on software. But if you make the software free, as BYD has with its self drive software, then you can sell more hardware.  This means that you have added network effects to hardware (Nvidia does this with CUDA, Apple do this to phones with IOS - but they don't own the whole manufacturing).  The issue for the US (and Europe) is that China does own all the hardware manufacturing for its network effect enabled hardware and it owns the supply chain too, and with a population of 1.4 billion,  it has stronger network effects than the US. There have been two eras of digital era distribution: PC era and smartphone era, but there have been three eras of internet business model: 1. Online only (social networks), 2. Online meets the real world (Uber, Airbnb etc.) 3. Online meets hardware and manufacturing.  The third era is exacerbated by the fact that AI has production rather than distribution network effects (software is cheaper to build not just cheaper to acquire users) so it can be used for manufactured goods which have smarts embedded. Europe fell behind with software so companies like German car manufacturers can't compete with EVs. Meanwhile the US not only has less network effects than China, it has less control of supply chains (e.g. batteries and components) so still relies on China for manufacturing or components so Tesla can't compete with BYD. China wins this third era of digitisation where it meets all physical goods.
This is the kind of leader America needs. The oratory alone is remarkable. Unfortunately, the choice is between a loose cannon and one firing blanks.

On October 13, 2022, a lone protestor staged an act of defiance on a bridge in Beijing.  He lit a fire to attract attention to himself, and unfurled a banner, demanding freedom from totalitarianism.  In his online manifesto posted on X (formerly Twitter), he called himself Peng Zai Zhou. He has not been heard from since. If alive, he is almost certainly being held in Chinese black prison, in unthinkably miserable conditions. We call on the Chinese Communist Party to answer the question: Where is the man who called himself Peng Zai Zhou, also believed to be Peng Li Fa? We demand a visit from independent humanitarian medical staff to determine his health, safety, and conditions of imprisonment. Does Zelenskyy was peace?  GROK answered my question: Yes, Volodymyr Zelenskyy has repeatedly stated that he wants peace for Ukraine. However, his vision for peace is specific: it must be 'just and lasting,' not a temporary truce that leaves Ukraine vulnerable to further aggression from Russia. As of March 3, 2025, he has emphasized that peace requires strong security guaranteesâ€”such as NATO membership or firm commitments from alliesâ€”to ensure Russia cannot attack again. For instance, in recent statements, like at a London summit on March 2, 2025, he said, 'For peace to be real, real security guarantees are needed,' showing his focus on ending the war sustainably rather than accepting a fragile ceasefire.  His actions, like pushing for Western military support and advocating for Ukraineâ€™s 'Victory Plan,' suggest he believes peace is achievable only from a position of strength, not through concessions that compromise Ukraineâ€™s sovereignty or safety. While some critics interpret his rejection of weaker ceasefire proposals as a desire to prolong the war, his public rhetoric consistently frames peace as the ultimate goalâ€”just on terms that protect Ukraine long-term. So, yes, he wants peace, but not at any cost.

In Canada, transparency and the principle of open justice are fundamental aspects of the judicial system. These principle emphasize the importance of not only delivering justice but also ensuring that it is visible and understood by the public. By maintaining transparency, the legal system can cultivate trust among citizens, promote accountability, and uphold the integrity of legal proceedings.   Open courts play a crucial role in allowing individuals to witness how justice is administered in a fair, impartial, and efficient manner. This transparency is essential for building public confidence in the judiciary and the legal system as a whole.  Court proceedings are more easily accessible in the United States compared to Canada. With the advancements in technology, there is no excuse for Canada to lag behind.  I encourage other provincial leaders and officials across Canada to follow suit and call for increased transparency in legal proceedings.

I've mostly been only retweeting recently, and for a rather simple reason: I'm rendered virtually speechless by what Israel is doing to Gaza and the world's unabashed complicity.  I knew that our leaders are corrupt and there are a lot of angry, bitter people in the world who externalize their misery onto innocent third parties.   But I did not predict that a country--Israel--could get away with burning children alive, indiscriminately bombing a civilian population, decimating entire families, targeting journalists, medical workers and their families for execution, shooting children in the head, starving 2 million people, corralling them into concentration camps with the promise of food--all live-streamed for the world to see, for 19 months.  And at most we get feeble protest from a few Western leaders about Israel going too far and mumblings about possibly maybe reconsidering support. And that's not to mention the vicious jubilations from a shocking number of Americans and Israelis.    It has become clear to me that evil is much more prevalent than I ever could have imagined before, and that many or most people can readily be convinced to support the most heinous of atrocities, or to ignore them.  The capacity of modern technology to simultaneously inflict degrees of suffering impossible centuries ago, and to broadcast that suffering to the world, makes evident that for all of our apparent advancement, we have not evolved morally as a species from the earliest days of human existence.

So, I spoke to people getting food at a food bank and here are some things I learned from those in need: 1. Everyone donates Kraft Mac and Cheese in the box. They can rarely use it because it needs milk and butter which is hard to get from regular food banks. 2. Boxed milk is a treasure, as kids need it for cereal which they also get a lot of. 3. Everyone donates pasta sauce and spaghetti noodles. 4. They cannot eat all the awesome canned veggies and soup unless you put a can opener in too or buy pop tops. 5. Oil is a luxury but needed for Rice a-Roni which they also get a lot of. 6. Spices or salt and pepper would be a real Christmas gift. 7. Tea bags and coffee make them feel like you care. 8. Sugar and flour are treats. 9. They fawn over fresh produce donated by farmers and grocery stores. 10. Seeds are cool in Spring and Summer because growing can be easy for some. 11. They rarely get fresh meat. 12. Tuna and crackers make a good lunch. 13. Hamburger Helper goes nowhere without ground beef. 14. They get lots of peanut butter and jelly but usually not sandwich bread. 15. Butter or margarine is nice too. 16. Eggs are a real commodity. 17. Cake mix and frosting makes it possible to make a childâ€™s birthday cake. 18. Dishwashing detergent is very expensive and is always appreciated. 19. Feminine hygiene products are a luxury and women will cry over that. 20. Everyone loves Stove Top Stuffing.  In all the years I have donated food at the Holidays, I bought what I thought they wanted, but have never asked. I am glad I did. If you are helping a Family this Christmas, maybe this can help you tailor it more. It does for me!

Agency is limited; women often need male permission for travel/work and even certain medical procedures.  Access to education is restricted in some fields. For the first time, it has been revealed that the Yoon Suk Yeol administration in South Korea confirmed through forensic analysis of the National Election Commission (NEC) servers that there was an election fraud involving 'computer manipulation'.  The controversy over 'computer manipulation' that altered election outcomes, which spread widely following the April 15, 2020 general election, has been confirmed by the state to be not just a suspicion but a reality, marking the first such acknowledgment in the history of constitutional governance.  According to an exclusive investigation by Sky Daily on the 5th, the National Intelligence Service (NIS) discovered records of election fraud through computer manipulation during a joint security inspection of the NEC servers from July to September last year.  Multiple intelligence sources report that the NIS urgently reported these findings to the presidential office at the time.  An intelligence source familiar with the matter told us, 'The NIS confirmed through a 5% forensic analysis of the NEC servers that there was election fraud in the past.'  However, under the Moon Jae-in administration, the NIS's investigative capabilities were significantly reduced, preventing immediate action, and the presidential office did not immediately transfer the case to the prosecution.  An anonymous source stated, 'The NIS's counter-espionage function has become virtually non-existent, so they tried to pass the investigation to the prosecution through a presidential report. However, it seems the presidential office did not immediately hand it over to the prosecution.'  For the prosecution to investigate, they need to obtain a search and seizure warrant from the court. However, there was concern that even if the prosecution requested such a warrant, the court might block it.  Under the current system, Supreme Court justices and judges at various levels hold positions as the chairpersons of the NEC and regional election commissions, and judges are implicated in election fraud suspicions. Numerous lawsuits alleging election fraud have consistently been dismissed by the courts until now.  However, during a state of martial law, search and seizure can be conducted without a court warrant.  Another source told us, '(Kim Gyu-hyun) the Director of the NIS mentioned the confirmed election fraud in a meeting with former intelligence agency heads during his tenure.'  This source corroborated the same facts, stating, 'After receiving a report from an NIS executive about the confirmation of past election manipulation through partial forensic analysis of the NEC servers, Director Kim immediately reported it to the presidential office.'  The NIS announced the results of the joint security inspection on October 10 last year, focusing only on the potential for hacking into the NEC's computer system, omitting this fact.  Meanwhile, there is speculation that President Yoon Suk Yeol's recent declaration of martial law might be related to investigating election fraud.  Previously, President Yoon declared martial law in a national address on the night of the 3rd, and the National Assembly passed a resolution demanding the lifting of martial law in an early morning plenary session on the 4th.  After President Yoon declared martial law, approximately 120 martial law troops and 100 police officers entered the NEC's Gwacheon office at around 00:30 on the 4th. Earlier, around 10 special agents, presumably, entered the NEC just two minutes after the martial law declaration at 22:30 on the 3rd.  It has also been newly discovered that about 50 martial law troops entered the NEC's Gwanak office, and approximately 130 martial law troops and 100 police officers moved into the Election Training Institute in Suwon, Gyeonggi, showing that the NEC was secured before the National Assembly.  Our newspaper initially obtained critical intelligence about the election fraud last summer, and after cross-checking last month, confirmed the information to be true. However, we have delayed the report to align with government steps and after internal discussions.

Is peace a victory for Ukraine?  It's impossible to say that a country that makes peace by giving part of its territory is victorious. And this is true. It's not only about Ukraine, but the Russians are defeating the second European army, supported by 40 countries.   The truth is that the spaced delivery of weapons and the low industrial capacity of allies have weighed in this defeat.  But, in general, the correlation of forces has been disproportional since February. Even in the best scenarios, Ukrainian chances would be minimal.  However, the article from The New York Times is very interesting because it draws attention to other points. The Russians may achieve a military victory, but in part, the plans of some allies are also being achieved. The Russians lost their biggest clients and the most valuable market in the world.   Europe still has problems with energy, but they have decided to avoid dealing with Russia. This is a defeat for the Russians, who are building bridges with other clients, but the damage has been done, and anyone who denies this isn't being honest.  While the large sanctions over Russia may not hold back their military, they are surely a headache for many of their companies. Sanctions can be ineffective in reaching their goals, but life is easier without them. In fact, Russia was hit by the new Western policy, but will leave this war with high morale and stronger ties with the East.   Is this a good long-term strategy for the West, who is vying for hegemony against the East? Personally, I don't think so.   But what is the West going to give to Ukraine? Don't come and tell me that Ukraine wasn't a proxy war. It's a proxy war where the West and Russians played a long game for almost two decades. Of course, many Ukrainians wanted to change their orbit, but the cost was very high.  What can the West give to Ukraine? Reconstruction?   Russia isn't going to allow a militarized Ukraine on its borders, so it's probable that in peace terms, Ukraine needs to limit its army and its military industry.   Will the West provide security guarantees for Ukraine? How? Will the sanctions remain on the negotiation table?  And the last question: Why would Putin have an urgency to negotiate if he is advancing on the entire front?   One thing is certain: the war has been unbalanced for a long time, and Ukraine has an improbable chance of victory.  Some readers will say that Ukraine hasn't been defeated yet or even that Ukraine is winning the war.   Well, all I have to say is that the Ukrainian army has descended into chaos, where everything has become scarce, from manpower to ammunition, personal equipment, vehicles, and, mainly, funds. And I'm one of the few persons who is reporting this since several months with total independence.  The Ukrainian army is now bravely surviving in defensive positions and creating media events to maintain foreign support. The country isn't defeated, but it's progressively happening.  Peace must be negotiated soon to avoid more deaths and destruction. But I don't see clearly what can be negotiated.

Note 4 AID: Ukraine even with its destroyed  economy spent more than allies on its war.  Ukraine military investment: $130bi Allies AID: 110bi While RU spent around 3-4x more.   Ukraine is paying it's war.   EU must do some self-criticism. GDP don't win wars.

Time to Stop the Hyper-Surveillance of Lawful Digital Asset Holders in the U.S.  What do I mean?  IRS Form 1040 poses this question near the top of page one--right under Filing Status:  'At any time during 2024, did you:  (a) receive (as a reward, award, or payment for property or services); or  (b) sell, exchange, or otherwise dispose of a digital asset (or a financial interest in a digital asset?)'  The question (presumably?) is designed to flag whether the taxpayer is likely to have realized capital gains or earned income from digital assets.  BUT the 1040 Form does NOT have a similar question asking tax filers whether they have engaged in transactions in gold, silver, stock, real estate, cars, antiques, baseball cards or any other asset class--even though those transactions could also trigger capital gains or income tax.  So why the special surveillance treatment of digital asset holders?  Why should the IRS be building a database of names, addresses, social security numbers (and other private information) of all lawful holders of digital asset in the U.S.?    --Asking for 50 million friends.  @DavidSacks

Translation:  Analysis of Khameneiâ€™s Miscalculations and the Illusion of the Islamic Republicâ€™s Survival  1. Khameneiâ€™s Core Assumption: Lack of Simultaneity Between Internal Protests and External Attacks  The Supreme Leader of the Islamic Republic operates under the belief that if a foreign attack occurs, the Iranian people will remain passive, waiting for the outcome rather than actively contributing to the regimeâ€™s downfall. This assumption is based on several factors:  . Public Fatigue and Disillusionment: Years of repression, lack of cohesive leadership within the opposition, and previous failed attempts at change have led many to believe that internal transformation is impossible without external intervention. â€¢ Hope for a Cost-Free Change: Many may assume that the U.S. and Israel will intervene, much like in Iraq and Libya, removing the regime without requiring a mass uprising. . Regime Propaganda and Psychological Manipulation: Through state-controlled media and psychological operations, the Islamic Republic seeks to frame any foreign attack as an assault on Iranâ€™s territorial integrity rather than an attack on the regime. This tactic is particularly effective among undecided segments of the population who fear instability more than they oppose the regime.  The belief that the Islamic Republic will fall without mass participation is a dangerous illusion. Several key reasons demonstrate why this assumption is incorrect:  . Foreign Attacks Alone Do Not Guarantee Regime Collapse: Past military interventions show that airstrikes and limited wars can severely weaken a regimeâ€™s military and economic infrastructure, but they do not necessarily lead to its downfall. Examples such as Syria, North Korea, and Venezuela prove that authoritarian governments can survive sanctions and military pressure. . People Are the Decisive Factor in Regime Change: Repressive regimes collapse primarily due to internal fractures. Nazi Germany only fell when both external and internal forces converged. In Iran, without widespread protests, strikes, and efforts to paralyze the regimeâ€™s security apparatus, external attacks will only delay the inevitable confrontation rather than resolve it. . Khameneiâ€™s Tactics for Survival: The Islamic Republic is already preparing for potential foreign strikes: . Increased Internal Repression: The regime is intensifying executions, imprisoning activists, and restricting internet access to prevent any organized resistance. . Manipulating Nationalist Sentiments: By portraying itself as the defender of Iranâ€™s sovereignty, the regime tries to convince the population that any attack is an attack on the nation itself rather than its authoritarian leadership. . Strengthening Ties with Russia and China: To counteract sanctions and military threats, the regime is deepening its reliance on Moscow and Beijing. However, these powers will prioritize their own interests over Tehranâ€™s survival if the regime significantly weakens.  3. The Solution: Synchronizing Internal Protests with External Pressure  If Iranians want to ensure the definitive collapse of the Islamic Republic, they must escalate their protests and strikes precisely when external attacks occur. This would create a dual crisis for the regime, reducing its ability to respond effectively. â€¢ Building Internal Resistance Networks: Organizing decentralized resistance cells, secure communication channels, and underground movements will ensure effective coordination among dissidents. â€¢ Striking at the Regimeâ€™s Power Centers: While external forces weaken the regime militarily, nationwide strikes must paralyze key sectors like the oil industry, transportation, and security forces. â€¢ Breaking the Climate of Fear and Inaction: The regimeâ€™s primary strategy is to keep people afraid and passive. Through media efforts, accurate information dissemination, and boosting public morale, this fear-based control must be dismantled.  Conclusion  Khamenei correctly understands that if internal protests and external pressure occur simultaneously, the Islamic Republic will not survive. That is why he is doing everything possible to suppress any domestic unrest before a potential foreign military strike. However, the Iranian people must also recognize that waiting for the regime to fall without active participation only serves the regimeâ€™s interests.  Only the strategic coordination of internal uprisings with external pressure can bring about the final collapse of the Islamic Republic.
